</div><div class="story-comment story-comment-even" commentindex="0">
  <div class="story-comment-metadata">from David Casseres on May 10, 2004 04:35:48
  
  </div>
  <div class="story-comment-body">Wow! I remember Burt Sloane hearing the news that Bob Belleville was gone.  He leaped in the air and clicked his heels together.  Not long after, he was gone too.

Andy, that's a great piece of writing about a strange, amazing time.  I have one or two memories to add.

The LaserWriter was an astonishing piece of technology.  I was in the PrintShop -- that is, the printing software group -- and I remember we hired in Bayles Holt, a brilliant engineer who had been at Xerox's labs in Rochester, New York, when they developed laser printing.  I can't quite remember whether this was before or after the PrintShop moved from the Lisa group to the Mac group.

When the LaserWriter was announced as a $7000 product, I remember being appalled.  How could a printer be worth $7000?  It seemed insane, especially when you could print really nice business documents with the dot-matrix printers we were selling for a couple of hundred bucks.

But that's why Steve was Steve and I wasn't.  $7000 was not too much, when the printer could be shared among multiple users in an office.  People bought a lot of those first-model LaserWriters and their successors.  There was a whole marketing push called "Macintosh Office," and most of us never grasped what it was about -- it was actually about only one thing, sharing a LaserWriter among numerous users.

This all laid the groundwork for the explosion of desktop publishing one or two years later when John Scull (not Sculley!) came along.  It was the founding of Apple's presence in the graphics publishing world, which Apple pretty much invented and still dominates.

</div>
  
