  <div class="story-comment-body">It might be interesting to add some field sales perspective to the whole story.  After all, we were the folks who took the Apple II into the schools nationwide, without which the company might not have been able to garner funds which enabled it to proceed with ensuing product development.  And, we were the ones who were tasked with roll-out and generating enthusiasm with dealers and end-users alike about the Mac when it came time to do so.  Trust me, Cupertino marketeers and advertising didn't do it all!  Even the University Consortium, desktop publishing, and even great GUI systems, etc., had to be sold locally to target customers in those days.  But it seems as though the field sales, training, and software engineering efforts may have been largely invisible to, or ignored by, some of you wonderful guys who provided us with the tools to successfully help grow the company.  
</div>
  
